<br>
I am a pianist/composer, and a right good one at that. Part of my living income comes from the music I write and produce in my home, though it is nowhere near enough to afford a full rental studio. So, I run a $15k studio out of my second bedroom.<br>
<br>
I only play the piano during the daylight hours without some form of muting or headphones, and I only record between noon and 8:00pm. Even when I *do* fire up the reference monitors and hook up the microphones I do so at reasonable levels. A couple of weeks ago a friend and I were just gearing up to lay down a piece of music when the police showed up a my front door. However, this was not the first visit from the law...<br>
<br>
A week prior to this particular visit I had just hooked up my home theater system, and had some friends over watching a movie at about 8pm. The cop showed up and pointed out that the bass was out of hand, and I soon realized that he was right. During the move the volume on my sub had been cranked, and the bass was really way too serious. I take full responsibility for the mistake, and have since tuned my system to more reasonable levels.<br>
<br>
Anyway, my friend and I are sitting there with our jaws on the floor with a cop at the door. I invited him up to the studio to have a listen, and he accepted. With a cop in the room, my friend and I went back to exactly what we were doing before. He got back to jamming a riff on his acoustic guitar, which was not mic'd or altered in any way, while I played backup on a phased Wurlitzer. The cop bobbed his head, danced around a little, and definitely enjoyed what we were doing. He told us that he did not believe that the noise was anywhere near too loud, but that he could not go to my neighbor's domecile as no name/address had been taken by dispatch. His suggestion was to meet my neighbor and talk it out. I gave this very cool officer a couple of my latest CDs and he left, promising we'd meet again. I believed him. This happened at approximately 1:30 in the afternoon.<br>
<br>
I went to my neighbor's house that afternoon. The neighbor in question is sitting at somewhere between 650-750lbs of pure hugeness, does not ever leave the house, and has no tolerance for anything whatsoever, I soon found. I explained that I wrote the music to make a living, and gave him a couple of copies of my *critically acclaimed* latest CD. Shameless, I know. I also gave him my phone number and asked that he call me next time instead of the cops. God knows he wouldn't walk his fat ass over to knock...<br>
<br>
A couple of days later, at 6:00 in the evening, I sat down to play the piano a bit. I had the volume at a reasonable level, but the call came quickly enough. I turned the levels down, but found them too low to really get any expression out of the Rach I was playing, so I had to resign the session. it was at that point I decided to call the landlady.<br>
<br>
As luck would have it I found my landlady on the back porch of a property just down the road a bit, and invited here over for a chat. She came up to the studio, listened, and agreed that the neighbor was being unreasonable. Even with the backing of the police and the owner of the property, I still looked for alternative ways to ease the situation. I rearranged part of my studio for better sound dispertion and ordered over $300 worth of dampening padding.<br>
<br>
I've lived in this place for over a month, and I've not been able to write a single note since I moved in. Today, with everyone on my side and all steps taken, I decided to play a little more, and perhaps even record a bit. A little while ago, at 10:30am, I opened up the piano. Halfway through a Scriaban the phone rang.<br>
<br>
&quot;Please turn that down. I'm getting tired of asking.&quot;<br>
<br>
And what did I do? I turned it down, and found that again I could not play at that level. So, I've stopped once again for the morbidly obese arse next door.<br>
<br>
Every morning at 3:00am his wife leaves the house in a Chevrolet pickup with echo pipes, waking up half the neighborhood. These folks are about to have police on their doorstep every single morning at 3:15 until they sell or fix that truck. If he even considers turning on his television, he'll be visited by the police. His poor wife works two jobs to support his eating necessity. On that note, I have *always* checked for her presence before playing the piano, simply out of neighborly courtesy. The poor woman needs her sleep, God knows.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I'm at the end of my rope on this. This guy's inability to deal with life is starting to bleed heavily into my passion for writing music. I've done all I can think to do to be nice about it. All out war is coming... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utoxxthewizard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Toxx The Wizard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 625<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/24/02 8:22:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3488.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Arserag neighbors</span><hr size=1> Perhaps your next composition could be inspired by these events. Writing with raw emotion is always a good thing. Good luck with what ever you do, just don't lose your love of music because this fella has a grudge against life. <p><center><img src="http://www.crosswinds.net/~ofthesword/sig1.txt"><br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=180294" target="_blank">Helius Wallace</a><br>
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=92172" target="_blank">Toxx Wyrmbane</a></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uglorianafrostglitter.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gloriana Frostglitter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1554<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/24/02 8:24:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3488.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Siding with the neighbors</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I only play the piano during the daylight hours without some form of muting or headphones, and I only record between noon and 8:00pm.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Going to have to side with the neighbors on this one.  The apartment complex is their home, not a place of business like a recording studio; they shouldn't have to listen to you play the piano for 8 hours a day.<br>
<br>
I'm sure you think your music is lovely, but lots of people like country music and I sure wouldn't want to listen to country music for 8 hours a day.<br>
